292;s:6:\"height\";i:300;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:9:\"image/png\";s:8:\"filesize\";i:124798;}s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:5:{s:4:\"file\";s:26:\"Illustration-1-150x150.png\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:9:\"image/png\";s:8:\"filesize\";i:33294;}s:12:\"medium_large\";a:5:{s:4:\"file\";s:26:\"Illustration-1-768x788.png\";s:5:\"width\";i:768;s:6:\"height\";i:788;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:9:\"image/png\";s:8:\"filesize\";i:848431;}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:12:{s:8:\"aperture\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";s:1:\"0\";s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"iso\";s:1:\"0\";s:13:\"shutter_speed\";s:1:\"0\";s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"orientation\";s:1:\"0\";s:8:\"keywords\";a:0:{}}}'),(174,36,'_thumbnail_id','60'),(175,61,'_edit_last','1'),(176,61,'_edit_lock','1662111276:1'),(177,63,'_edit_last','1'),(178,63,'_edit_lock','1662110978:1'),(179,61,'about_title','Cop Out: Automation in the Criminal Legal System'),(180,61,'_about_title','field_62b59bd815102'),(181,61,'about_subtitle','Systems of policing and punishment in the U.S. are undergoing a major change: police, judges, prosecutors and other legal authorities are increasingly using algorithmic technologies when making decisions that have critical consequences in the lives of in dividuals and communities.'),(182,61,'_about_subtitle','field_62b59be315103'),(183,61,'bold_part_content_paragraph','Algorithms are ubiquitous in the criminal legal system. As we all move through the world, a mosaic of overlapping surveillance technologies collect and store information about us'),(184,61,'_bold_part_content_paragraph','field_62b59beb15104'),(185,61,'content_paragraph','Law enforcement agencies, adjudicator s and corrections officials use algorithms to filter through the billions of pieces of data collected through these surveillance technologies and make calculations about which neighborhoods to police, what offense to charge someone with, how long that pers on should be incarcerated and when they will be free again.'),(186,61,'_content_paragraph','field_62b59bfa15105'),(187,61,'second_paragraph','The companies that build the algorithms behind policing technologies take for granted existing approaches to policing and punishment, approaches that communities are actively contesting. What should the policeâ€™s role be? What is the real meaning of public safety? Are there better ways to prevent and redress harm? Those are questions that must always be part of ongoing democratic deliberation about justice. But policing algorithms codify assumptions about justice, the reby preserving the status quo.\r\n\r\nMost of us are unaware of the ways that algorithmic tools, trained on information gathered through continuous mass surveillance, are influencing legal system actors who have enormous power over our lives. This projectâ€™s goal is to illuminate that fact and to begin the process of making an opaque and disorienting system legible.'),(188,61,'_second_paragraph','field_62b59c0b15106'),(189,69,'about_title','Cop Out: Automation in the Criminal Legal System'),(190,69,'_about_title','field_62b59bd815102'),(191,69,'about_subtitle',' Systems of policing and punishment in the U.S. are undergoing a major change: police, judges, prosecutors and other legal authorities are increasingly using algorithmic technologies when making decisions that have critical consequences in the lives of in dividuals and communities.'),(192,69,'_about_subtitle','field_62b59be315103'),(193,69,'bold_part_content_paragraph','Algorithms are ubiquitous in the criminal legal system. As we all move through the world, a mosaic of overlapping surveillance technologies collect and store information about us'),(194,69,'_bold_part_content_paragraph','field_62b59beb15104'),(195,69,'content_paragraph',' Law enforcement agencies, adjudicator s and corrections officials use algorithms to filter through the billions of pieces of data collected through these surveillance technologies and make calculations about which neighborhoods to police, what offense to charge someone with, how long that pers on should be incarcerated and when they will be free again.'),(196,69,'_content_paragraph','field_62b59bfa15105'),(197,69,'second_paragraph','d'),(198,69,'_second_paragraph','field_62b59c0b15106'),(199,70,'about_title','Cop Out: Automation in the Criminal Legal System'),(200,70,'_about_title','field_62b59bd815102'),(201,70,'about_subtitle',' Systems of policing and punishment in the U.S. are undergoing a major change: police, judges, prosecutors and other legal authorities are increasingly using algorithmic technologies when making decisions that have critical consequences in the lives of in dividuals and communities.'),(202,70,'_about_subtitle','field_62b59be315103'),(203,70,'bold_part_content_paragraph','Algorithms are ubiquitous in the criminal legal system. As we all move through the world, a mosaic of overlapping surveillance technologies collect and store information about us'),(204,70,'_bold_part_content_paragraph','field_62b59beb15104'),(205,70,'content_paragraph',' Law enforcement agencies, adjudicator s and corrections officials use algorithms to filter through the billions of pieces of data collected through these surveillance technologies and make calculations about which neighborhoods to police, what offense to charge someone with, how long that pers on should be incarcerated and when they will be free again.'),(206,70,'_content_paragraph','field_62b59bfa15105'),(207,70,'second_paragraph','The companies that build the algorithms behind policing technologies take for granted existing\r\napproaches to policing and punishment, approaches that communities are actively contesting.\r\nWhat should the policeâ€™s rol\r\ne be? What is the real meaning of public safety? Are there better\r\nways to prevent and redress harm? Those are questions that must always be part of ongoing\r\ndemocratic deliberation about justice. But policing algorithms codify assumptions about justice,\r\nthe\r\nreby preserving the status quo.\r\nMost of us are unaware of the ways that algorithmic tools, trained on information gathered\r\nthrough continuous mass surveillance, are influencing legal system actors who have enormous\r\npower over our lives. This projectâ€™s g\r\noal is to illuminate that fact and to begin the process of\r\nmaking an opaque and disorienting system legible.'),(208,70,'_second_paragraph','field_62b59c0b15106'),(209,71,'about_title','Cop Out: Automation in the Criminal Legal System'),(210,71,'_about_title','field_62b59bd815102'),(211,71,'about_subtitle',' Systems of policing and punishment in the U.S. are undergoing a major change: police, judges, prosecutors and other legal authorities are increasingly using algorithmic technologies when making decisions that have critical consequences in the lives of in dividuals and communities.'),(212,71,'_about_subtitle','field_62b59be315103'),(213,71,'bold_part_content_paragraph','Algorithms are ubiquitous in the criminal legal system. As we all move through the world, a mosaic of overlapping surveillance technologies collect and store information about us'),(214,71,'_bold_part_content_paragraph','field_62b59beb15104'),(215,71,'content_paragraph',' Law enforcement agencies, adjudicator s and corrections officials use algorithms to filter through the billions of pieces of data collected through these surveillance technologies and make calculations about which neighborhoods to police, what offense to charge someone with, how long that pers on should be incarcerated and when they will be free again.'),(216,71,'_content_paragraph','field_62b59bfa15105'),(217,71,'second_paragraph','The companies that build the algorithms behind policing technologies take for granted existing approaches to policing and punishment, approaches that communities are actively contesting. What should the policeâ€™s role be? What is the real meaning of public safety? Are there better ways to prevent and redress harm? Those are questions that must always be part of ongoing democratic deliberation about justice. But policing algorithms codify assumptions about justice, the reby preserving the status quo.\r\n\r\nMost of us are unaware of the ways that algorithmic tools, trained on information gathered through continuous mass surveillance, are influencing legal system actors who have enormous power over our lives. This projectâ€™s goal is to illuminate that fact and to begin the process of making an opaque and disorienting system legible.'),(218,71,'_second_paragraph','field_62b59c0b15106'),(219,79,'_edit_last','1'),(220,79,'_edit_lock','1656659683:1'),(221,83,'_edit_last','1'),(222,83,'first_name_and_last_name','Jameson Spivack'),(223,83,'_first_name_and_last_name','field_62b5a93078014'),(224,83,'job_title','Associate'),(225,83,'_job_title','field_62b5a95a78015'),(226,83,'_edit_lock','1656937431:1'),(227,84,'_wp_attached_file','2022/06/Illustration-2..png'),(228,84,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:6:{s:5:\"width\";i:998;s:6:\"height\";i:1024;s:4:\"file\";s:27:\"2022/06/Illustration-2..png\";s:8:\"filesize\";i:1582694;s:5:\"sizes\";a:3:{s:6:\"medium\";a:5:{s:4:\"file\";s:27:\"Illustration-2.-292x300.png\";s:5:\"width\";i:292;s:6:\"height\";i:300;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:9:\"image/png\";s:8:\"filesize\";i:136565;}s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:5:{s:4:\"file\";s:27:\"Illustration-2.-150x150.png\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:9:\"image/png\";s:8:\"filesize\";i:36165;}s:12:\"medium_large\";a:5:{s:4:\"file\";s:27:\"Illustration-2.-768x788.png\";s:5:\"width\";i:768;s:6:\"height\";i:788;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:9:\"image/png\";s:8:\"filesize\";i:895754;}}s:10:\"image_meta\";a:12:{s:8:\"aperture\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"credit\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"camera\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"caption\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"created_timestamp\";s:1:\"0\";s:9:\"copyright\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"focal_length\";s:1:\"0\";s:3:\"iso\";s:1:\"0\";s:13:\"shutter_speed\";s:1:\"0\";s:5:\"title\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"orientation\";s:1:\"0\";s:8:\"keywords\";a:0:{}}}'),(229,38,'_thumbnail_id','84'),(230,38,'title','Arrested'),(231,38,'_title','field_62b56ffd11759'),(232,38,'text_in_left_part','You are driving to work in your car when you hear a police siren directly behind you. Getting out of your car, youâ€™re ordered to get on your knees and put your hands in the air, and told that youâ€™re under arrest. The officer arrests you and brings you to jail for booking.'),(233,38,'_text_in_left_part','field_62b570091175a'),(234,38,'title_for_pop-up_1','Automated license-plate readers (ALPRs)'),(235,38,'_title_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5701d1175b'),(236,38,'description_for_pop-up_1','After identifying you and obtaining a warrant for your arrest, the officer uses an ALPR to track down the location of your vehicle.'),(237,38,'_description_for_pop-up_1','field_62b570331175e'),(238,38,'subtitle_1','Automated license plate readers (ALPRs)'),(239,38,'_subtitle_1','field_62b570927557b'),(240,38,'more_info_for_pop-up_1','Automated license plate readers (also sometimes called automatic number-plate recognition) involve cameras that capture license plate numbers, digitize them, and upload them into a database searchable by law enforcement. This data is stored for long periods of time, allowing law enforcement to track individualsâ€™ locations and movement. According to vendors, this information can tell police where a plate has been, identify travel patterns, and link vehicles to one another.'),(241,38,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(242,38,'title_for_pop-up_2',''),(243,38,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(244,38,'description_for_pop-up_2',''),(245,38,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(246,38,'subtitle_2',''),(247,38,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(248,38,'more_info_for_pop-up_2',''),(249,38,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(250,38,'title_for_pop-up_3',''),(251,38,'_title_for_pop-up_3'