llected through these surveillance technologies and make calculations about which neighborhoods to police, what offense to charge someone with, how long that pers on should be incarcerated and when they will be free again.'),(1827,203,'_content_paragraph','field_62b59bfa15105'),(1828,203,'second_paragraph','The companies that build the algorithms behind policing technologies take for granted existing approaches to policing and punishment, approaches that communities are actively contesting. What should the policeâ€™s role be? What is the real meaning of public safety? Are there better ways to prevent and redress harm? Those are questions that must always be part of ongoing democratic deliberation about justice. But policing algorithms codify assumptions about justice, the reby preserving the status quo.\r\n\r\nMost of us are unaware of the ways that algorithmic tools, trained on information gathered through continuous mass surveillance, are influencing legal system actors who have enormous power over our lives. This projectâ€™s goal is to illuminate that fact and to begin the process of making an opaque and disorienting system legible.'),(1829,203,'_second_paragraph','field_62b59c0b15106'),(1830,203,'download_title','--Lorem Ipsum Dolor Sit Amet--'),(1831,203,'_download_title','field_62b94d9d21dc3'),(1832,203,'download_bold_part_paragraph','This website is accompanied by an essay expanding on the harms of algorithms in policing and punishment and an appendix containing an '),(1833,203,'_download_bold_part_paragraph','field_62b94da721dc4'),(1834,203,'download_paragraph',' annotated bibliography of some of the most important scholarship on the use of algorithms in the criminal legal system.'),(1835,203,'_download_paragraph','field_62b94e6921dc5'),(1836,203,'acknowledgements_bold_part_paragraph','This project would not be possible without the tireless research and advocacy of our friends and allies who also seek a more just and equitable American criminal legal system.'),(1837,203,'_acknowledgements_bold_part_paragraph','field_62b94fd7582da'),(1838,203,'acknowledgements_paragraph','This includes lawyers, advocates, journalists, scholars and activists, as well a s everyone else who filed public records requests, investigated how law enforcement uses algorithmic technologies and wrote about their legal, ethical and moral implications. It also includes those who have been subjected to carceral technologies and have bravely shared their stories with the public. Their work forms the basis of this project. Special thanks go to Andrew Ferguson, Jerome Greco and Freddy Martinez for their critical guidance and expertise. The entire team at the Center, past and present, al so deserves recognition for the countless ways they helped out with this project: Alvaro Bedoya, Katie Evans, Clare Garvie, Cynthia Khoo, Laura Moy, Harrison Rudolph, Korica Simon, Emily Tucker, David Vladeck, Nina Wang and Serena Zets. We are also gratefu l for the Centerâ€™s research assistants and summer fellows; our copy editor, Joy Metcalf; and our design and web development firm, nclud. The Center on Privacy & Technology at Georgetown Law is supported by the Ford Foundation, the Kresge Foundation, the Open Society Foundations, the MacArthur Foundation, Luminate, the Media Democracy Fund, the Seldin/Haring - Smith Foundation and Georgetown University Law Center.'),(1839,203,'_acknowledgements_paragraph','field_62b9502f55110'),(1840,203,'paper_file','199'),(1841,203,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(1842,203,'app_file','202'),(1843,203,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(1844,203,'paper_file_title',''),(1845,203,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(1846,203,'app_file_title',''),(1847,203,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(1848,203,'acknowledgements_part_paragraph','This project would not be possible without the tireless research and advocacy of our friends and allies who also seek a more just and equitable American criminal legal system.'),(1849,203,'_acknowledgements_part_paragraph','field_62b94fd7582da'),(1850,203,'acknowledgements_main_paragraph','This includes lawyers, advocates, journalists, scholars and activists, as well a s everyone else who filed public records requests, investigated how law enforcement uses algorithmic technologies and wrote about their legal, ethical and moral implications. It also includes those who have been subjected to carceral technologies and have bravely shared their stories with the public. Their work forms the basis of this project. Special thanks go to Andrew Ferguson, Jerome Greco and Freddy Martinez for their critical guidance and expertise. The entire team at the Center, past and present, al so deserves recognition for the countless ways they helped out with this project: Alvaro Bedoya, Katie Evans, Clare Garvie, Cynthia Khoo, Laura Moy, Harrison Rudolph, Korica Simon, Emily Tucker, David Vladeck, Nina Wang and Serena Zets. We are also gratefu l for the Centerâ€™s research assistants and summer fellows; our copy editor, Joy Metcalf; and our design and web development firm, nclud. The Center on Privacy & Technology at'),(1851,203,'_acknowledgements_main_paragraph','field_62b9502f55110'),(1852,203,'acknowledgements_title','--Lorem Ipsum Dolor Sit Amet--'),(1853,203,'_acknowledgements_title','field_62beaabf262c9'),(1854,204,'background_image','16'),(1855,204,'_background_image','field_62b557afaa324'),(1856,204,'title',' Cop Out: Automation in the Criminal Legal System'),(1857,204,'_title','field_62b557c0aa325'),(1858,204,'bold_part_of_subtitle','Systems of policing and punishment in the U.S. are undergoing a major change:'),(1859,204,'_bold_part_of_subtitle','field_62b557c8aa326'),(1860,204,'subtitle','police,  dges, prosecutors and other legal authorities are increasingly using algorithmic technologies when making decisions that have critical consequences in the lives of in dividuals and communities.'),(1861,204,'_subtitle','field_62b557d8aa327'),(1862,204,'paper_file_title',''),(1863,204,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(1864,204,'paper_file','199'),(1865,204,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(1866,204,'app_file_title',''),(1867,204,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(1868,204,'app_file','202'),(1869,204,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(1885,42,'paper_file_title',''),(1886,42,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(1887,42,'paper_file',''),(1888,42,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(1889,42,'app_file_title',''),(1890,42,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(1891,42,'app_file',''),(1892,42,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(1893,216,'title','Pre-trial jail'),(1894,216,'_title','field_62b56ffd11759'),(1895,216,'text_in_left_part','You are told that youâ€™ve been arrested for shoplifting, but are not given any information about how you were how you were identified, or the fact that you were being monitored as an â€œat-risk individual.â€ While held in jail, you are given maximum supervision.'),(1896,216,'_text_in_left_part','field_62b570091175a'),(1897,216,'title_for_pop-up_1','Face recognition'),(1898,216,'_title_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5701d1175b'),(1899,216,'description_for_pop-up_1','Unbeknownst to you, the police officer had previously run the photo of a suspect in a shoplifting case through a face recognition system. You were returned as a match for the suspect, which formed the basis of the warrant for your arrest.'),(1900,216,'_description_for_pop-up_1','field_62b570331175e'),(1901,216,'subtitle_1','Basics'),(1902,216,'_subtitle_1','field_62b570927557b'),(1903,216,'more_info_for_pop-up_1','Face recognition technology, (often called â€œfacialâ€ recognition), is an algorithmic biometric tool that which compares two face images to determine the likelihood they are a match. Law enforcement purportedly uses face recognition to produce leads when trying to identify people in photos or video footage. There are generally two types of face recognition: one-to-one matching, which compares two photos to one another to verify theyâ€™re the same person; and one-to-many matching, which compares one photo to a large database in order to identify someone. In the latter, officers upload a â€œprobeâ€ photo of a face in question, and an algorithm analyzes its features, compares it to a database of face photos, and then issues a numerical score reflecting the similarity of the â€œprobeâ€ photo face to other faces in the database. \r\n\r\nWhen analyzing a photo, the algorithm first detects the presence of a face. Then, it â€œnormalizesâ€ the image, scaling and rotating so itâ€™s in a standard position for comparison. Next, it extracts facial features like eyes and nose from the image. Finally, it compares these features to those in another photo, assigning a score based on how similar they are. Face recognition refers to this specific process, as distinct from other face analysis tools that purport to classify peopleâ€™s faces by factors like gender or age.\r\n\r\nFor more on the basics of face recognition technology, see:'),(1904,216,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(1905,216,'title_for_pop-up_2','Crime forecasting'),(1906,216,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(1907,216,'description_for_pop-up_2','You were designated as an â€œat-riskâ€ individual by a crime forecasting algorithm, not necessarily as a perpetrator of crime, but potentially as a victim. As such, you were subject to heightened monitoring by law enforcement.'),(1908,216,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(1909,216,'subtitle_2','Basics'),(1910,216,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(1911,216,'more_info_for_pop-up_2','â€œCrime forecastingâ€ refers to two separate but related processes: predictive policing and data-driven prosecution. Both processes use historical crime data to make predictions about future crime, using these predictions to inform who is policed and prosecuted. Based on existing â€œhot spotâ€ theories of policing, crime forecasting assumes there are particular areas and individuals who are more â€œat-riskâ€ for criminal activity. Automated tools analyze data such as where past crimes occurred and features of the local environment to determine if a location is â€œat-risk,â€ or if an individual is â€œlikelyâ€ to commit or be the victim of a crime. Law enforcement sees these tools as more efficient and less biased than humans, capable of making quick decisions while also cutting costs. \r\n\r\n'),(1912,216,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(1913,216,'title_for_pop-up_3','Case management, planning, and supervision (jail)'),(1914,216,'_title_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5702b1175d'),(1915,216,'description_for_pop-up_3','A RAT tool has considered you to be at a high risk for violence, so you are given maximum security while held in jail awaiting trial.'),(1916,216,'_description_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5706511762'),(1917,216,'subtitle_3','RAT: jail case management, planning, and supervision'),(1918,216,'_subtitle_3','field_62b57eb6e3372'),(1919,216,'more_info_for_pop-up_3','In jails, RATs are used to supplement case management, a process intended to reduce risk by ensuring individuals have access to needed resources. Case management refers to the process in which officials evaluate incarcerated peoplesâ€™ needs and risks, and connect them to appropriate services and programs. Intended to provide continuity of care between incarceration and the community, case management considers factors related to physical and mental health, substance abuse, education, housing, and employment.\r\n\r\nIn this context RATs serve to automate the evaluation and resource recommendation functions. Theyâ€™re used to funnel scarce resourcesâ€”attention and programming from case managersâ€”towards the supposedly highest risk individuals. These tools are not only diagnostic but distributive as well; they are meant to provide case managers with recommendations about how to best reduce individualsâ€™ risks based on their evaluated needs.'),(1920,216,'_more_info_for_pop-up_3','field_62b570c37557e'),(1921,216,'lilst_items_item_1','Clare Garvie, Alvaro Bedoya, Jonathan Frankle, The Perpetual Line-Up: Unregulated Police Face Recognition in America, https://www.perpetuallineup.org/ '),(1922,216,'_lilst_items_item_1','field_62b570ea75580'),(1923,216,'lilst_items_item_2','Stan Z. Li, Anil K. Jain, â€œThe Handbook of Face Recognition,â€ Second Edition, https://www.researchgate.net/publication/235709405_Handbook_of_Face_Recognition_the_second_edition'),(1924,216,'_lilst_items_item_2','field_62b570f575581'),(1925,216,'lilst_items_item_3',''),(1926,216,'_lilst_items_item_3','field_62b570f675582'),(1927,216,'lilst_items_item_4',''),(1928,216,'_lilst_items_item_4','field_62b570f775583'),(1929,216,'lilst_items_item_5',''),(1930,216,'_lilst_items_item_5','field_62b5a234d64c3'),(1931,216,'lilst_items',''),(1932,216,'_lilst_items','field_62b570c97557f'),(1933,216,'lilst_items_2_item_1','National Institute of Justice Office of Justice Programs, â€œPredictive Policing,â€ https://www.nij.gov/topics/law-enforcement/strategies/predictive-policing/Pages/welcome.aspx '),(1934,216,'_lilst_items_2_item_1','field_62b5a238d64c5'),(1935,216,'lilst_items_2_item_2','Andrew Ferguson, Big Data Prosecution and Brady: https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3397292 '),(1936,216,'_lilst_items_2_item_2','field_62b5a238d64c6'),(1937,216,'lilst_items_2_item_3','Andrew J. Ferguson, Predictive Policing Theory, The Cambridge Handbook of Policing in the United States (ed. Tamara Rice Lave & Eric J. Miller), Cambridge Univ. Press (2019)'),(1938,216,'_lilst_items_2_item_3','field_62b5a238d64c7'),(1939,216,'lilst_items_2_item_4','John S. Hollywood, Brian McInnis, Walter L. Perry, Carter C. Price, Susan C. Smith, Predictive Policing: The Role of Crime Forecasting in Law Enforcement Operations, RAND Corporation, available at https://ebookcentral.proquest.com/lib/georgetown/reader.action?docID=1437438 '),(1940,216,'_lilst_items_2_item_4'