ich compares two photos to one another to verify theyâ€™re the same person; and one-to-many matching, which compares one photo to a large database in order to identify someone. In the latter, officers upload a â€œprobeâ€ photo of a face in question, and an algorithm analyzes its features, compares it to a database of face photos, and then issues a numerical score reflecting the similarity of the â€œprobeâ€ photo face to other faces in the database. \r\n\r\nWhen analyzing a photo, the algorithm first detects the presence of a face. Then, it â€œnormalizesâ€ the image, scaling and rotating so itâ€™s in a standard position for comparison. Next, it extracts facial features like eyes and nose from the image. Finally, it compares these features to those in another photo, assigning a score based on how similar they are. Face recognition refers to this specific process, as distinct from other face analysis tools that purport to classify peopleâ€™s faces by factors like gender or age.\r\n\r\n'),(1964,217,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(1965,217,'title_for_pop-up_2','Crime forecasting'),(1966,217,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(1967,217,'description_for_pop-up_2','You were designated as an â€œat-riskâ€ individual by a crime forecasting algorithm, not necessarily as a perpetrator of crime, but potentially as a victim. As such, you were subject to heightened monitoring by law enforcement.'),(1968,217,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(1969,217,'subtitle_2','Basics'),(1970,217,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(1971,217,'more_info_for_pop-up_2','â€œCrime forecastingâ€ refers to two separate but related processes: predictive policing and data-driven prosecution. Both processes use historical crime data to make predictions about future crime, using these predictions to inform who is policed and prosecuted. Based on existing â€œhot spotâ€ theories of policing, crime forecasting assumes there are particular areas and individuals who