17,'lilst_items_2_item_5','Sarah Brayne, Big Data Surveillance: The Case of Policing, American Sociological Review, Vol. 82(5) 977-1008 (2017)'),(2002,217,'_lilst_items_2_item_5','field_62b5a238d64c9'),(2003,217,'lilst_items_2',''),(2004,217,'_lilst_items_2','field_62b5a238d64c4'),(2005,217,'paper_file_title',''),(2006,217,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2007,217,'paper_file',''),(2008,217,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2009,217,'app_file_title',''),(2010,217,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2011,217,'app_file',''),(2012,217,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2013,218,'title','Pre-trial jail'),(2014,218,'_title','field_62b56ffd11759'),(2015,218,'text_in_left_part','<strong>You are told that youâ€™ve been arrested for shoplifting, but are not given any information about how you were how you were identified,</strong> or the fact that you were being monitored as an â€œat-risk individual.â€ While held in jail, you are given maximum supervision.'),(2016,218,'_text_in_left_part','field_62b570091175a'),(2017,218,'title_for_pop-up_1','Face recognition'),(2018,218,'_title_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5701d1175b'),(2019,218,'description_for_pop-up_1','Unbeknownst to you, the police officer had previously run the photo of a suspect in a shoplifting case through a face recognition system. You were returned as a match for the suspect, which formed the basis of the warrant for your arrest.'),(2020,218,'_description_for_pop-up_1','field_62b570331175e'),(2021,218,'subtitle_1','Basics'),(2022,218,'_subtitle_1','field_62b570927557b'),(2023,218,'more_info_for_pop-up_1','Face recognition technology, (often called â€œfacialâ€ recognition), is an algorithmic biometric tool that which compares two face images to determine the likelihood they are a match. Law enforcement purportedly uses face recognition to produce leads when trying to identify people in photos or video footage. There are generally two types of face recognition: one-to-one matching, which compares two photos to one another to verify theyâ€™re the same person; and one-to-many matching, which compares one photo to a large database in order to identify someone. In the latter, officers upload a â€œprobeâ€ photo of a face in question, and an algorithm analyzes its features, compares it to a database of face photos, and then issues a numerical score reflecting the similarity of the â€œprobeâ€ photo face to other faces in the database. \r\n\r\nWhen analyzing a photo, the algorithm first detects the presence of a face. Then, it â€œnormalizesâ€ the image, scaling and rotating so itâ€™s in a standard position for comparison. Next, it extracts facial features like eyes and nose from the image. Finally, it compares these features to those in another photo, assigning a score based on how similar they are. Face recognition refers to this specific process, as distinct from other face analysis tools that purport to classify peopleâ€™s faces by factors like gender or age.\r\n\r\n'),(2024,218,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(2025,218,'title_for_pop-up_2','Crime forecasting'),(2026,218,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(2027,218,'description_for_pop-up_2','You were designated as an â€œat-riskâ€ individual by a crime forecasting algorithm, not necessarily as a perpetrator of crime, but potentially as a victim. As such, you were subject to heightened monitoring by law enforcement.'),(2028,218,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(2029,218,'subtitle_2','Basics'),(2030,218,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(2031,218,'more_info_for_pop-up_2','â€œCrime forecastingâ€ refers to two separate but related processes: predictive policing and data-driven prosecution. Both processes use historical crime data to make predictions about future crime, using these predictions to inform who is policed and prosecuted. Based on existing â€œhot spotâ€ theories of policing, crime forecasting assumes there are particular areas and individuals who are more â€œat-riskâ€ for criminal activity. Automated tools analyze data such as where past crimes occurred and features of the local environment to determine if a location is â€œat-risk,â€ or if an individual is â€œlikelyâ€ to commit or be the victim of a crime. Law enforcement sees these tools as more efficient and less biased than humans, capable of making quick decisions while also cutting costs. \r\n\r\n'),(2032,218,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(2033,218,'title_for_pop-up_3','Case management, planning, and supervision (jail)'),(2034,218,'_title_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5702b1175d'),(2035,218,'description_for_pop-up_3','A RAT tool has considered you to be at a high risk for violence, so you are given maximum security while held in jail awaiting trial.'),(2036,218,'_description_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5706511762'),(2037,218,'subtitle_3','RAT: jail case management, planning, and supervision'),(2038,218,'_subtitle_3','field_62b57eb6e3372'),(2039,218,'more_info_for_pop-up_3','In jails, RATs are used to supplement case management, a process intended to reduce risk by ensuring individuals have access to needed resources. Case management refers to the process in which officials evaluate incarcerated peoplesâ€™ needs and risks, and connect them to appropriate services and programs. Intended to provide continuity of care between incarceration and the community, case management considers factors related to physical and mental health, substance abuse, education, housing, and employment.\r\n\r\nIn this context RATs serve to automate the evaluation and resource recommendation functions. Theyâ€™re used to funnel scarce resourcesâ€”attention and programming from case managersâ€”towards the supposedly highest risk individuals. These tools are not only diagnostic but distributive as well; they are meant to provide case managers with recommendations about how to best reduce individualsâ€™ risks based on their evaluated needs.'),(2040,218,'_more_info_for_pop-up_3','field_62b570c37557e'),(2041,218,'lilst_items_item_1','Clare Garvie, Alvaro Bedoya, Jonathan Frankle, The Perpetual Line-Up: Unregulated Police Face Recognition in America, https://www.perpetuallineup.org/ '),(2042,218,'_lilst_items_item_1','field_62b570ea75580'),(2043,218,'lilst_items_item_2','Stan Z. Li, Anil K. Jain, â€œThe Handbook of Face Recognition,â€ Second Edition, https://www.researchgate.net/publication/235709405_Handbook_of_Face_Recognition_the_second_edition'),(2044,218,'_lilst_items_item_2','field_62b570f575581'),(2045,218,'lilst_items_item_3',''),(2046,218,'_lilst_items_item_3','field_62b570f675582'),(2047,218,'lilst_items_item_4',''),(2048,218,'_lilst_items_item_4','field_62b570f775583'),(2049,218,'lilst_items_item_5',''),(2050,218,'_lilst_items_item_5','field_62b5a234d64c3'),(2051,218,'lilst_items',''),(2052,218,'_lilst_items','field_62b570c97557f'),(2053,218,'lilst_items_2_item_1','National Institute of Justice Office of Justice Programs, â€œPredictive Policing,â€ https://www.nij.gov/topics/law-enforcement/strategies/predictive-policing/Pages/welcome.aspx '),(2054,218,'_lilst_items_2_item_1','field_62b5a238d64c5'),(2055,218,'lilst_items_2_item_2','Andrew Ferguson, Big Data Prosecution and Brady: https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3397292 '),(2056,218,'_lilst_items_2_item_2','field_62b5a238d64c6'),(2057,218,'lilst_items_2_item_3','Andrew J. Ferguson, Predictive Policing Theory, The Cambridge Handbook of Policing in the United States (ed. Tamara Rice Lave & Eric J. Miller), Cambridge Univ. Press (2019)'),(2058,218,'_lilst_items_2_item_3','field_62b5a238d64c7'),(2059,218,'lilst_items_2_item_4','John S. Hollywood, Brian McInnis, Walter L. Perry, Carter C. Price, Susan C. Smith, Predictive Policing: The Role of Crime Forecasting in Law Enforcement Operations, RAND Corporation, available at https://ebookcentral.proquest.com/lib/georgetown/reader.action?docID=1437438 '),(2060,218,'_lilst_items_2_item_4','field_62b5a238d64c8'),(2061,218,'lilst_items_2_item_5','Sarah Brayne, Big Data Surveillance: The Case of Policing, American Sociological Review, Vol. 82(5) 977-1008 (2017)'),(2062,218,'_lilst_items_2_item_5','field_62b5a238d64c9'),(2063,218,'lilst_items_2',''),(2064,218,'_lilst_items_2','field_62b5a238d64c4'),(2065,218,'paper_file_title',''),(2066,218,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2067,218,'paper_file',''),(2068,218,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2069,218,'app_file_title',''),(2070,218,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2071,218,'app_file',''),(2072,218,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2073,40,'paper_file_title',''),(2074,40,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2075,40,'paper_file',''),(2076,40,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2077,40,'app_file_title',''),(2078,40,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2079,40,'app_file',''),(2080,40,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2081,219,'title','Booking â€¨& bail'),(2082,219,'_title','field_62b56ffd11759'),(2083,219,'text_in_left_part','<strong>You are booked into jail</strong>. You are told that, due to an assessment of your history and circumstances, you are a flight risk and therefore denied bail.'),(2084,219,'_text_in_left_part','field_62b570091175a'),(2085,219,'title_for_pop-up_1','Risk assessment technologies'),(2086,219,'_title_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5701d1175b'),(2087,219,'description_for_pop-up_1','Risk assessment tools inform a series of critical decisions regarding your experiences in jail, court, prison, and release contexts. Your supposed level of dangerousness, as determined by these tools, influence whether you get bail, the level of supervision you get while incarcerated, sentencing, and possibility for parole.'),(2088,219,'_description_for_pop-up_1','field_62b570331175e'),(2089,219,'subtitle_1','Risk assessment tools (RATs)'),(2090,219,'_subtitle_1','field_62b570927557b'),(2091,219,'more_info_for_pop-up_1','Risk assessment tools (RATs) are a general class of algorithms that purport to predict the likelihood of an individual engaging in certain unwanted behavior in the future. Most commonly in the criminal legal system, they are used to forecast future misconduct; specifically, the chance an individual will skip bail, commit another crime, or be rearrested. They are also used to anticipate challenges incarcerated people will have during transitions into and out of institutionalization. \r\n\r\nWith â€œriskâ€ in mind, criminal legal system officials make decisions about peoplesâ€™ liberty, supervision, and criminogenic needs. There are six main stages at which RATs are employed: pretrial, jail, prison, release, parole, and probation. Most notably, RATs are used for setting bail, case management in jails, sentencing, case management in prisons, informing discretionary release/parole, case management during parole, and determining probation. However, they can theoretically be used at any point during an individualâ€™s interaction with the criminal legal system.\r\n\r\nFor more on the basics of risk assessment tools, see:'),(2092,219,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(2093,219,'title_for_pop-up_2','Bail (pretrial)'),(2094,219,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(2095,219,'description_for_pop-up_2','A RAT tool has considered you a flight risk, and thus you have been denied bail.'),(2096,219,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(2097,219,'subtitle_2','Risk assessment tools (RATs)'),(2098,219,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(2099,219,'more_info_for_pop-up_2','A defendant often has their first encounter with an RAT before trial when their bail is being set. Here, RATs are used in one of two ways: to gauge the likelihood of an individualâ€™s failure to appear (FTA) at their trial, or to assess their likelihood of committing another crime before trial. Historically, bail was used exclusively as a means to ensure court appearances and discourage flight. However, due to a number of political shifts, the concept of an individualâ€™s â€œdangerousnessâ€ to the community became a major factor in bail determination. RATs, when used to set bail, now score people based on their FTA likelihood and risk of committing a crime after pretrial release.\r\n\r\nInitially, some critics of mass incarceration supported this application of RATs as a way to decrease pretrial detention rates and eliminate the disadvantage poor people face with cash bail. But these tools led to only small increases in pretrial release, and, in fact, increased FTAs and pretrial crime rates. Moreover, they yet again exhibit the limitations of data-driven technologies: because RATs are trained on specific data, they fail to reflect the true complex realities of the criminal legal system. Across place and time, RATs apply a one-size-fits-all approach to different contexts not necessarily compatible with the originally collected data. For example, RATs are often trained on older data; but if a jurisdiction has since instituted pretrial reforms, the RAT will reflect outdated practices rather than current ones. If a new diversion program is introduced to decrease pretrial detention and recidivism, the RAT does not take this into account, hiding any potential effects the reform has and reinforcing historical trends.'),(2100,219,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(2101,219,'title_for_pop-up_3',''),(2102,219,'_title_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5702b1175d'),(2103,219,'description_for_pop-up_3',''),(2104,219,'_description_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5706511762'),(2105,219,'subtitle_3',''),(2106,219,'_subtitle_3','field_62b57eb6e3372'),(2107,219,'more_info_for_pop-up_3',''),(2108,219,'_more_info_for_pop-up_3','field_62b570c37557e'),(2109,219,'lilst_items_item_1','â€œPublic Safety Risk Assessment Clearinghouse,â€ Bureau of Justice Assistance, US Department of Justice, https://psrac.bja.ojp.gov/ '),(2110,219,'_lilst_items_item_1','field_62b570ea75580'),(2111,219,'lilst_items_item_2','â€œUse of Valid Actuarial Assessments of Risks and Needs,â€ National Parole Resource Center, https://nationalparoleresourcecenter.org/action-guide-use-of-valid-actuarial-assessments-of-risks-and-needs/selecting-and-validating-an-assessment-instrument.htm '),(2112,219,'_lilst_items_item_2','field_62b570f575581'),(2113,219,'lilst_items_item_3','Alex Chohlas-Wood, â€œUnderstanding risk assessment instruments in criminal justice,â€ https://www.brookings.edu/research/understanding-risk-assessment-instruments-in-criminal-justice/'),(2114,219,'_lilst_items_item_3','field_62b570f675582'),(2115,219,'lilst_items_item_4',''),(2116,219,'_lilst_items_item_4','field_62b570f775583'),(2117,219,'lilst_items_item_5',''),(2118,219,'_lilst_items_item_5','field_62b5a234d64c3'),(2119,219,'lilst_items',''),(2120,219,'_lilst_items','field_62b570c97557f'),(2121,219,'lilst_items_2_item_1',''),(2122,219,'_lilst_items_2_item_1','field_62b5a238d64c5'),(2123,219,'lilst_items_2_item_2',''),(2124,219,'_lilst_items_2_item_2','field_62b5a238d64c6'),(2125,219,'lilst_items_2_item_3',''),(2126,219,'_lilst_items_2_item_3','field_62b5a238d64c7'),(2127,219,'lilst_items_2_item_4',''),(2128,219,'_lilst_items_2_item_4','field_62b5a238d64c8'),(2129,219,'lilst_items_2_item_5',''),(2130,219,'_lilst_items_2_item_5','field_62b5a238d64c9'),(2131,219,'lilst_items_2',''),(2132,219,'_lilst_items_2','field_62b5a238d64c4'),(2133,219,'paper_file_title',''),(2134,219,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2135,219,'paper_file',''),(2136,219,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2137,219,'app_file_title',''),(2138,219,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2139,219,'app_file',''),(2140,219,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2141,36,'lilst_items_item_5',''),(2142,36,'_lilst_items_item_5','field_62b5a234d64c3'),(2143,36,'lilst_items_2_item_1',''),(2144,36,'_lilst_items_2_item_1','field_62b5a238d64c5'),(2145,36,'lilst_items_2_item_2',''),(2146,36,'_lilst_items_2_item_2','field_62b5a238d64c6'),(2147,36,'lilst_items_2_item_3',''),(2148,36,'_lilst_items_2_item_3','field_62b5a238d64c7'),(2149,36,'lilst_items_2_item_4',''),(2150,36,'_lilst_items_2_item_4','field_62b5a238d64c8'),(2151,36,'lilst_items_2_item_5',''),(2152,36,'_lilst_items_2_item_5','field_62b5a238d64c9'),(2153,36,'lilst_items_2',''),(2154,36,'_lilst_items_2','field_62b5a238d64c4'),(2155,36,'paper_file_title',''),(2156,36,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2157,36,'paper_file',''),(2158,36,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2159,36,'app_file_title',''),(2160,36,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2161,36,'app_file',''),(2162,36,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2163,59,'lilst_items_item_5',''),(2164,59,'_lilst_items_item_5','field_62b5a234d64c3'),(2165,59,'lilst_items_2_item_1',''),(2166,59,'_lilst_items_2_item_1','field_62b5a238d64c5'),(2167,59,'lilst_items_2_item_2',''),(2168,59,'_lilst_items_2_item_2','field_62b5a238d64c6'),(2169,59,'lilst_items_2_item_3',''),(2170,59,'_lilst_items_2_item_3','field_62b5a238d64c7'),(2171,59,'lilst_items_2_item_4',''),(2172,59,'_lilst_items_2_item_4','field_62b5a238d64c8'),(2173,59,'lilst_items_2_item_5',''),(2174,59,'_lilst_items_2_item_5','field_62b5a238d64c9'),(2175,59,'lilst_items_2',''),(2176,59,'_lilst_items_2','field_62b5a238d64c4'),(2177,59,'paper_file_title',''),(2178,59,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2179,59,'paper_file',''),(2180,59,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2181,59,'app_file_title',''),(2182,59,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2183,59,'app_file',''),(2184,59,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2185,44,'paper_file_title',''),(2186,44,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2187,44,'paper_file',''),(2188,44,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2189,44,'app_file_title',''),(2190,44,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2191,44,'app_file',''),(2192,44,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2193,220,'title','Trial & sentencing'),(2194,220,'_title','field_62b56ffd11759'),(2195,220,'text_in_left_part','<strong>Your trial date arrives.</strong> The judge has decided that, as a result of the risk you pose for committing another crime, you are given a three-year sentence. You are found guilty, and sentenced to three years with the possibility of parole.'),(2196,220,'_text_in_left_part','field_62b570091175a'),(2197,220,'title_for_pop-up_1','Sentencing'),(2198,220,'_title_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5701d1175b'),(2199,220,'description_for_pop-up_1','A RAT tool has determined you are at risk of committing another crime in the future, and so you are sentenced to three years in prison with the possibility of parole.'),(2200,220,'_description_for_pop-up_1','field_62b570331175e'),(2201,220,'subtitle_1','RAT: sentencing'),(2202,220,'_subtitle_1','field_62b570927557b'),(2203,220,'more_info_for_pop-up_1','Once at trial, RATs are used to inform judgesâ€™ sentencing determinations. RATs purporting to predict the risk of an individual committing another crime in the futureâ€”their â€œdangerousnessâ€â€”guide judges when deciding how and for how long to punish those convicted. In contrast to pretrial RATs, which are used to make binary decisions (for example, if someone is labeled as a flight risk or likely to commit a crime before trial, they are detained; if not, they are released), sentencing RATs are used to make even more complex, multi-faceted decisions. Judges must determine what kind of punishment or remedy is warranted, and, if incarcerated, the length of time.'),(2204,220,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(2205,220,'title_for_pop-up_2',''),(2206,220,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(2207,220,'description_for_pop-up_2',''),(2208,220,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(2209,220,'subtitle_2',''),(2210,220,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(2211,220,'more_info_for_pop-up_2',''),(2212,220,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(2213,220,'title_for_pop-up_3',''),(2214,220,'_title_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5702b1175d'),(2215,220,'description_for_pop-up_3',''),(2216,220,'_description_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5706511762'),(2217,220,'subtitle_3',''),(2218,220,'_subtitle_3','field_62b57eb6e3372'),(2219,220,'more_info_for_pop-up_3',''),(2220,220,'_more_info_for_pop-up_3','field_62b570c37557e'),(2221,220,'lilst_items_item_1',''),(2222,220,'_lilst_items_item_1','field_62b570ea75580'),(2223,220,'lilst_items_item_2',''),(2224,220,'_lilst_items_item_2','field_62b570f575581'),(2225,220,'lilst_items_item_3',''),(2226,220,'_lilst_items_item_3','field_62b570f675582'),(2227,220,'lilst_items_item_4',''),(2228,220,'_lilst_items_item_4','field_62b570f775583'),(2229,220,'lilst_items_item_5',''),(2230,220,'_lilst_items_item_5','field_62b5a234d64c3'),(2231,220,'lilst_items',''),(2232,220,'_lilst_items','field_62b570c97557f'),(2233,220,'lilst_items_2_item_1',''),(2234,220,'_lilst_items_2_item_1','field_62b5a238d64c5'),(2235,220,'lilst_items_2_item_2',''),(2236,220,'_lilst_items_2_item_2','field_62b5a238d64c6'),(2237,220,'lilst_items_2_item_3',''),(2238,220,'_lilst_items_2_item_3','field_62b5a238d64c7'),(2239,220,'lilst_items_2_item_4',''),(2240,220,'_lilst_items_2_item_4','field_62b5a238d64c8'),(2241,220,'lilst_items_2_item_5',''),(2242,220,'_lilst_items_2_item_5','field_62b5a238d64c9'),(2243,220,'lilst_items_2',''),(2244,220,'_lilst_items_2','field_62b5a238d64c4'),(2245,220,'paper_file_title',''),(2246,220,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2247,220,'paper_file',''),(2248,220,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2249,220,'app_file_title',''),(2250,220,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2251,220,'app_file',''),(2252,220,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2253,46,'paper_file_title',''),(2254,46,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2255,46,'paper_file',''),(2256,46,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2257,46,'app_file_title',''),(2258,46,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2259,46,'app_file',''),(2260,46,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2261,221,'title','Prison'),(2262,221,'_title','field_62b56ffd11759'),(2263,221,'text_in_left_part','<strong>You have been sentenced to prison time with the possibility of parole.</strong> While in prison, you are recommended for a job skills training and labor market reentry program, which you attend.'),(2264,221,'_text_in_left_part','field_62b570091175a'),(2265,221,'title_for_pop-up_1','Case management, planning, and supervision (prison)'),(2266,221,'_title_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5701d1175b'),(2267,221,'description_for_pop-up_1','A RAT tool has determined that because of your life circumstances, you are eligible for a job skills training and reentry program.'),(2268,221,'_description_for_pop-up_1','field_62b570331175e'),(2269,221,'subtitle_1','RAT: prison case management, planning, and supervision'),(2270,221,'_subtitle_1','field_62b570927557b'),(2271,221,'more_info_for_pop-up_1','Incarcerated individuals in prisons are subject to similar case management RATs as they are in jails. In both, the purpose is the same: to evaluate risks and needs, and connect individuals to programming.'),(2272,221,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(2273,221,'title_for_pop-up_2',''),(2274,221,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(2275,221,'description_for_pop-up_2',''),(2276,221,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(2277,221,'subtitle_2',''),(2278,221,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(2279,221,'more_info_for_pop-up_2',''),(2280,221,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(2281,221,'title_for_pop-up_3',''),(2282,221,'_title_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5702b1175d'),(2283,221,'description_for_pop-up_3',''),(2284,221,'_description_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5706511762'),(2285,221,'subtitle_3',''),(2286,221,'_subtitle_3','field_62b57eb6e3372'),(2287,221,'more_info_for_pop-up_3',''),(2288,221,'_more_info_for_pop-up_3','field_62b570c37557e'),(2289,221,'lilst_items_item_1',''),(2290,221,'_lilst_items_item_1','field_62b570ea75580'),(2291,221,'lilst_items_item_2',''),(2292,221,'_lilst_items_item_2','field_62b570f575581'),(2293,221,'lilst_items_item_3',''),(2294,221,'_lilst_items_item_3','field_62b570f675582'),(2295,221,'lilst_items_item_4',''),(2296,221,'_lilst_items_item_4','field_62b570f775583'),(2297,221,'lilst_items_item_5',''),(2298,221,'_lilst_items_item_5','field_62b5a234d64c3'),(2299,221,'lilst_items',''),(2300,221,'_lilst_items','field_62b570c97557f'),(2301,221,'lilst_items_2_item_1',''),(2302,221,'_lilst_items_2_item_1','field_62b5a238d64c5'),(2303,221,'lilst_items_2_item_2',''),(2304,221,'_lilst_items_2_item_2','field_62b5a238d64c6'),(2305,221,'lilst_items_2_item_3',''),(2306,221,'_lilst_items_2_item_3','field_62b5a238d64c7'),(2307,221,'lilst_items_2_item_4',''),(2308,221,'_lilst_items_2_item_4','field_62b5a238d64c8'),(2309,221,'lilst_items_2_item_5',''),(2310,221,'_lilst_items_2_item_5','field_62b5a238d64c9'),(2311,221,'lilst_items_2',''),(2312,221,'_lilst_items_2','field_62b5a238d64c4'),(2313,221,'paper_file_title',''),(2314,221,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2315,221,'paper_file',''),(2316,221,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2317,221,'app_file_title',''),(2318,221,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2319,221,'app_file',''),(2320,221,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2321,48,'paper_file_title',''),(2322,48,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2323,48,'paper_file',''),(2324,48,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2325,48,'app_file_title',''),(2326,48,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2327,48,'app_file',''),(2328,48,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2329,222,'title','Release assessment'),(2330,222,'_title','field_62b56ffd11759'),(2331,222,'text_in_left_part','<strong>After serving a year and a half of your three-year sentence, you are told there is a chance you may be released early for good behavior.</strong>\r\n\r\nYou have a meeting with _____, who asks you a few questions and looks over your history. The next day, you are informed that you have been assessed as still at risk to the community, so will not be released. However, you are told thereâ€™s an opportunity to reassess in a year.'),(2332,222,'_text_in_left_part','field_62b570091175a'),(2333,222,'title_for_pop-up_1','Discretionary release/parole'),(2334,222,'_title_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5701d1175b'),(2335,222,'description_for_pop-up_1','A RAT tool originally determined you still posed a threat committing another crime, and were denied early release. However, when evaluated a year later, a RAT tool determines you no longer pose a significant threat and are released from prison early on parole.'),(2336,222,'_description_for_pop-up_1','field_62b570331175e'),(2337,222,'subtitle_1','RAT: discretionary release/parole'),(2338,222,'_subtitle_1','field_62b570927557b'),(2339,222,'more_info_for_pop-up_1','When deciding whether to release an incarcerated person early on parole (also known as discretionary release), parole boards will consult RATs to determine the individualâ€™s risk of recidivism. This decision is based on factors such as crime severity, length of incarceration, behavior while incarcerated, criminal history, and mental health. Other factors such as education, gender, and age are also taken into account. At this stage, RATs are intended to anticipate an individual reoffending, particularly in a violent way, and are sometimes customized for specific groups (for example, targeting recidivism risk for sex offenders).'),(2340,222,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(2341,222,'title_for_pop-up_2',''),(2342,222,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(2343,222,'description_for_pop-up_2',''),(2344,222,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(2345,222,'subtitle_2',''),(2346,222,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(2347,222,'more_info_for_pop-up_2',''),(2348,222,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(2349,222,'title_for_pop-up_3',''),(2350,222,'_title_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5702b1175d'),(2351,222,'description_for_pop-up_3',''),(2352,222,'_description_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5706511762'),(2353,222,'subtitle_3',''),(2354,222,'_subtitle_3','field_62b57eb6e3372'),(2355,222,'more_info_for_pop-up_3',''),(2356,222,'_more_info_for_pop-up_3','field_62b570c37557e'),(2357,222,'lilst_items_item_1',''),(2358,222,'_lilst_items_item_1','field_62b570ea75580'),(2359,222,'lilst_items_item_2',''),(2360,222,'_lilst_items_item_2','field_62b570f575581'),(2361,222,'lilst_items_item_3',''),(2362,222,'_lilst_items_item_3','field_62b570f675582'),(2363,222,'lilst_items_item_4',''),(2364,222,'_lilst_items_item_4','field_62b570f775583'),(2365,222,'lilst_items_item_5',''),(2366,222,'_lilst_items_item_5','field_62b5a234d64c3'),(2367,222,'lilst_items',''),(2368,222,'_lilst_items','field_62b570c97557f'),(2369,222,'lilst_items_2_item_1',''),(2370,222,'_lilst_items_2_item_1','field_62b5a238d64c5'),(2371,222,'lilst_items_2_item_2',''),(2372,222,'_lilst_items_2_item_2','field_62b5a238d64c6'),(2373,222,'lilst_items_2_item_3',''),(2374,222,'_lilst_items_2_item_3','field_62b5a238d64c7'),(2375,222,'lilst_items_2_item_4',''),(2376,222,'_lilst_items_2_item_4','field_62b5a238d64c8'),(2377,222,'lilst_items_2_item_5',''),(2378,222,'_lilst_items_2_item_5','field_62b5a238d64c9'),(2379,222,'lilst_items_2',''),(2380,222,'_lilst_items_2','field_62b5a238d64c4'),(2381,222,'paper_file_title',''),(2382,222,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2383,222,'paper_file',''),(2384,222,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2385,222,'app_file_title',''),(2386,222,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2387,222,'app_file',''),(2388,222,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2389,50,'paper_file_title',''),(2390,50,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(2391,50,'paper_file',''),(2392,50,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(2393,50,'app_file_title',''),(2394,50,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(2395,50,'app_file',''),(2396,50,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(2397,223,'title','Release'),(2398,223,'_title','field_62b56ffd11759'),(2399,223,'text_in_left_part','<strong>One year later, six months shy of completing your full sentence, you are assessed once again.</strong> This time, you are determined to no longer be a risk to the community, and are released six months early on parole.'),(2400,223,'_text_in_left_part','field_62b570091175a'),(2401,223,'title_for_pop-up_1','Discretionary release/parole'),(2402,223,'_title_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5701d1175b'),(2403,223,'description_for_pop-up_1','A RAT tool originally determined you still posed a threat committing another crime, and were denied early release. However, when evaluated a year later, a RAT tool determines you no longer pose a significant threat and are released from prison early on parole.'),(2404,223,'_description_for_pop-up_1','field_62b570331175e'),(2405,223,'subtitle_1','RAT: discretionary release/parole'),(2406,223,'_subtitle_1','field_62b570927557b'),(2407,223,'more_info_for_pop-up_1','When deciding whether to release an incarcerated person early on parole (also known as discretionary release), parole boards will consult RATs to determine the individualâ€™s risk of recidivism. This decision is based on factors such as crime severity, length of incarceration, behavior while incarcerated, criminal history, and mental health. Other factors such as education, gender, and age are also taken into account. At this stage, RATs are intended to anticipate an individual reoffending, particularly in a violent way, and are sometimes customized for specific groups (for example, targeting recidivism risk for sex offenders).'),(2408,223,'_more_info_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5709e7557c'),(2409,223,'title_for_pop-up_2',''),(2410,223,'_title_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570281175c'),(2411,223,'description_for_pop-up_2',''),(2412,223,'_description_for_pop-up_2','field_62b5706211761'),(2413,223,'subtitle_2',''),(2414,223,'_subtitle_2','field_62b57eb4e3371'),(2415,223,'more_info_for_pop-up_2',''),(2416,223,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(2417,223,'title_for_pop-up_3',''),(2418,223,'_title_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5702b1175d'),(2419,223,'description_for_pop-u