n and recidivism, the RAT does not take this into account, hiding any potential effects the reform has and reinforcing historical trends.'),(3164,253,'_more_info_for_pop-up_2','field_62b570b77557d'),(3165,253,'title_for_pop-up_3',''),(3166,253,'_title_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5702b1175d'),(3167,253,'description_for_pop-up_3',''),(3168,253,'_description_for_pop-up_3','field_62b5706511762'),(3169,253,'subtitle_3',''),(3170,253,'_subtitle_3','field_62b57eb6e3372'),(3171,253,'more_info_for_pop-up_3',''),(3172,253,'_more_info_for_pop-up_3','field_62b570c37557e'),(3173,253,'lilst_items_item_1','â€œPublic Safety Risk Assessment Clearinghouse,â€ Bureau of Justice Assistance, US Department of Justice, https://psrac.bja.ojp.gov/ '),(3174,253,'_lilst_items_item_1','field_62b570ea75580'),(3175,253,'lilst_items_item_2','â€œUse of Valid Actuarial Assessments of Risks and Needs,â€ National Parole Resource Center, https://nationalparoleresourcecenter.org/action-guide-use-of-valid-actuarial-assessments-of-risks-and-needs/selecting-and-validating-an-assessment-instrument.htm '),(3176,253,'_lilst_items_item_2','field_62b570f575581'),(3177,253,'lilst_items_item_3','Alex Chohlas-Wood, â€œUnderstanding risk assessment instruments in criminal justice,â€ https://www.brookings.edu/research/understanding-risk-assessment-instruments-in-criminal-justice/'),(3178,253,'_lilst_items_item_3','field_62b570f675582'),(3179,253,'lilst_items_item_4',''),(3180,253,'_lilst_items_item_4','field_62b570f775583'),(3181,253,'lilst_items_item_5',''),(3182,253,'_lilst_items_item_5','field_62b5a234d64c3'),(3183,253,'lilst_items',''),(3184,253,'_lilst_items','field_62b570c97557f'),(3185,253,'lilst_items_2_item_1',''),(3186,253,'_lilst_items_2_item_1','field_62b5a238d64c5'),(3187,253,'lilst_items_2_item_2',''),(3188,253,'_lilst_items_2_item_2','field_62b5a238d64c6'),(3189,253,'lilst_items_2_item_3',''),(3190,253,'_lilst_items_2_item_3','field_62b5a238d64c7'),(3191,253,'lilst_items_2_item_4',''),(3192,253,'_lilst_items_2_item_4','field_62b5a238d64c8'),(3193,253,'lilst_items_2_item_5',''),(3194,253,'_lilst_items_2_item_5','field_62b5a238d64c9'),(3195,253,'lilst_items_2',''),(3196,253,'_lilst_items_2','field_62b5a238d64c4'),(3197,253,'paper_file_title',''),(3198,253,'_paper_file_title','field_62b962bd14753'),(3199,253,'paper_file',''),(3200,253,'_paper_file','field_62b5cb0fefce1'),(3201,253,'app_file_title',''),(3202,253,'_app_file_title','field_62b96421bf4ca'),(3203,253,'app_file',''),(3204,253,'_app_file','field_62b5cb1eefce2'),(3205,183,'_thumbnail_id','177'),(3206,256,'title','Parole'),(3207,256,'_title','field_62b56ffd11759'),(3208,256,'text_in_left_part','<strong>Once you have been released back into the community on parole, you are still under supervision of a parole officer.</strong> According to your parole officer, you are considered at risk for drug use, and are required to attend anti-drug use courses as well as submit urine samples every week. After six months is up, you are no longer on parole and do not need to report to your officer.\r\n\r\n<strong>Once you have been released back into the community on parole, you are still under supervision of a parole officer.</strong> According to your parole officer, you are considered at risk for drug use, and are required to attend anti-drug use courses as well as submit urine samples every week. After six months is up, you are no longer on parole and do not need to report to your officer.\r\n\r\n<strong>Once you have been released back into the community on parole, you are still under supervision of a parole officer.</strong> According to your parole officer, you are considered at risk for drug use, and are required to attend anti-drug use courses as well as submit urine samples every week. After six months is up, you are no longer on parole and do not need to report to your officer.\r\n\r\n<strong>Once you have been released back into the community on parole, you are still under supervision of a parole officer.</strong> According to your parole officer, you are considered at risk for drug use, and are required to attend anti-drug use courses as well as submit urine samples every week. After six months is up, you are no longer on parole and do not need to report to your officer.\r\n\r\n<strong>Once you have been released back into the community on parole, you are still under supervision of a parole officer.</strong> According to your parole officer, you are considered at risk for drug use, and are required to attend anti-drug use courses as well as submit urine samples every week. After six months is up, you are no longer on parole and do not need to report to your officer.'),(3209,256,'_text_in_left_part','field_62b570091175a'),(3210,256,'title_for_pop-up_1','Case management (parole)'),(3211,256,'_title_for_pop-up_1','field_62b5701d1175b'),(3212,256,'description_for_pop-up_1','Even after you have been released from prison, a RAT tool has determined that you are still a risk for drug use. You are required to attend anti-drug meetings and submit weekly urine samples to your parole officer.'),(3213,256,'_description_for_pop-up_1','field_62b570331175e'),(3214,256,'subtitle_1','RAT: parole case management'),(3215,256,'_subtitle_1','field_62b570927557b'),(3216,256,'more_info_for_pop-up_1','During parole, RATs are used for case management, much the same as they are in jails and prisons. Parole authorities are responsible for ensuring previously incarcerated individuals are not rearrested or break conditions of their parole. They employ RATs to evaluate risk factors for recidivism, and to provide services to minimize this risk. RATs also measure and track â€œprogressâ€ of individuals over the course of their time in probation, and in the criminal legal system overall. Like case management at other decision points, during parole RATs are specialized to evaluate risks related to violence, sexual offenses, health issues, addiction, mental illness, behavior, attitudes, and other areas.'),(3217,